							<font size="3"><b>&nbsp;</b></font>
					    </td>
					</tr>
					
					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Rogue's In-Combat Button Creatin' Basics</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:">smellyone</a> | 
		            6/25/2001 3:53:56 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">I've read through many of these rogue guides and haven't seen these addressed, so without being redundant (hopefully), here it goes.<BR>
<BR>
First a quick little note about social button creation and the frontal-backstab-extra-attack schtick.  This is the way I do it and there of course maybe even easier methods I don't know of.  The 6 slots that are allowed for designation of skills in your abilities menu are numbered 1-6, starting from the top left and going right down the next 2 rows.  So the top left slot is #1, and the bottom right slot is #6.  <BR>
<BR>
For ease of explanation, I put my backstab skill in slot #1, my pickpocket skill in #2, hide in #3, and sneak in #4.<BR>
<BR>
Also as most of us backstabbers should know, if you are attacking from the front-side of a MOB and hit backstab, it is used as an extra attack with your piercer. I haven't played in a while so I'm not sure if auto-attack can be on or must be off before you backstab, but in this case it will be off for a split second. <BR>
<BR>
So in order to pickpocket an angry, clawing, snarling whatever without missing a beat, you might think about creating a button I call 'jackem'.  Please remember that these buttons are intended to be used after you are already fightin' away.<BR>
<BR>
First, find yourself a nice blank social button from your socials list.  Call it what you will, like I said I call mine jackem, 'cause that's what happens. On the 4 lines of commands that you can use, type these:<BR>
/attack<BR>
/doability 1<BR>
/doability 2<BR>
/attack<BR>
<BR>
Since you are already in auto-attack mode from your initial engagement, the first line turns auto-attack off.<BR>
 <BR>
The second line (backstab in this case) throws an extra attack because like I said before you are attacking from the front. So although you have auto-attack off, you will attack with your primary piercer.  Hence the not skipping a beat part.<BR>
<BR>
The third line (pickpocket in this case) allows you an attempt at a little five-fingered discount, which occurs immediately after you shove your piercing weapon into said MOB's sternum. This happens because the first line turned off auto-attack, allowing the pilfer attempt.  <BR>
<BR>
The fourth line gets you jabbin' again.<BR>
<BR>
The beauty of it is that it all occurs in about a second, if that.<BR>
<BR>
The reuse times of backstab and pickpocket are, whatdya know, VERY close in duration.  So if you take this button you've created and put it in a hotbutton slot on the left, and have your abilities menu open on the right side, you can easily gauge when to hit jackem again because you can see when your backstab/pickpocket buttons light up again.  <BR>
<BR>
As far as I've been able to tell in actual experience and what I've gleaned from the various sites, the dough you snake from the MOB DOES NOT come from the same money pool that the corpse will have on it.  So any ornery group members will have nothin' to say as you relentlessly pickpocket your way to better skill.  The only thing you will have to share are actual MOB inventory items that you snag, because those won't be on the corpse. But I've never had anyone ask for any item to be shared, that's just my experience though. <BR>
<BR>
Once I heard/read/dreamed about the 'doability' command, which I believe can also be achieved by typing /do #, it opened up a whole new realm of lightning-quick in-combat button possibilities.  <BR>
<BR>
The next progression for me was the 'evade' button, consisting of:<BR>
/attack<BR>
/doability 3 (hide in this example)<BR>
/attack<BR>
<BR>
You simply stop fighting for a nanosecond, disappear, then start fighting again.  I'm not sure exactly how effective this is, but in my experiences a MOB will at times miss you, and if anything else your will increase your hide skill.  <BR>
<BR>
Next I created the 'retreat' button in case I am really getting the crap beat out of me tanking, like so many PCs expect us rogues to do, which if you haven't noticed we are by no means built for except for emergencies:<BR>
/attack<BR>
/doability 3<BR>
/doability 4<BR>
<BR>
This disengages us completely from combat because it turns off attack and then immediately hide/sneaks our thieving arses.  The only problem is if the old hate-o-meter is too high, or the MOB's lvl is too high, or both, I'm not sure,  but the MOB may just quickly step to ya and finish you off.  I figure it's worth a try either way, and until I learn differently, I'll continue to do so.  <BR>
<BR>
I was trying to develop some kind of of attack off/duck/duck/attack on button, but I moved from a computer that could handle EQ to one that couldn't so I haven't played in days unfortunately.  But I'll bet my fellow rogues get the picture.  <BR>
<BR>
Well I hope I haven't taken up too much space or stolen another post's thunder.  Anyways stab n' snag on, comrades.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;When in doubt, go to 7-11.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Stenchor McReex<BR>
Backstabber of the 21st artery<BR>
Tunare server (soon)<BR>

			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
